description: From be- +‎ bay (“to bend”), from Middle English beien, beȝen, from Old English bīeġan (“to bend, turn, turn back, incline, depress, abase, humiliate, subject, persuade, convert”), from Proto-Germanic *bi- + *baugijaną.

verbs.description: bebay (third-person singular simple present bebays, present participle bebaying, simple past and past participle bebayed)

entries.meaning: (rare, transitive) To bay around or about; embay; hem in; surround.
